This works as it should:
```python

        d1 = {
            'a': 1,
            'b': {
                'c': 2,
                'd': {'e': 3},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        
        d2 = {
            'a': 1,
            'b': {
                'c': 3,
                'd': {'e': 3},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        assert_that(d1).is_equal_to(d2, ignore=('b','c'))
```
However, the ignore doesn't seem to work with nesting levels greater than two. For example:
This code passes when it shouldn't:

```python
        d1 = {
            'a': 1,
            'b': {
                'c': 2,
                'd': {'e': 3},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        
        d2 = {
            'a': 1,
            'b': {
                'c': 2,
                'd': {'e': 4},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        assert_that(d1).is_equal_to(d2, ignore=('b','f','g'))
```
or more strangely, this also passes:
```python
        d1 = {
            'a': 1,
            'b': {
                'c': 2,
                'd': {'e': 3},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        
        d2 = {
            'a': 2,
            'b': {
                'c': 2,
                'd': {'e': 4},
                'f': {'g': 5}
                 }
            }
        assert_that(d1).is_equal_to(d2, ignore=('b','f','g'))
```

I am using version 1.0 of assertpy

Although in the documentation I haven't found any example with more than 2 level nested keys I was expecting it would be possible.

I'd like to be able to assert that one dictionary is a subset of another dictionary. The current dictionary assertions don't seem to be able to handle that case.

``` Python
def is_sub_dict(sub_dict, dictionary):
    return all((k in dictionary and dictionary[k] == v) for k, v in sub_dict.iteritems())

d1 = {'a':'2', 'b':'3'}
d2 = {'a':'2', 'b':'3','c':'4'}
d3 = {'d':'5'}
d4 = {'a':'foo'}

is_sub_dict(d1, d2)
True

is_sub_dict(d3, d2)
False

In [9]: is_sub_dict(d4, d2)
False
```

I can work on a PR for this
